	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Rice sector trends and trade policy measures in West Africa</h1>

			
			<h4>
												12 August 2012
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>With poor rains impacting on production, USDA estimates (excluding Nigeria) show a 13% decrease in West African milled rice production for the 2011/12 marketing year (MY) compared to 2010/11. Rice production is estimated to fall by 25% in Mali, 27% in Senegal, 17% in Niger and 12% in Burkina Faso, 17.6% in Chad and 16% in Guinea Bissau. Imports of rice are projected to increase by 8%, in part covering the decline in production, however consumption of rice is projected to fall by 1% in 2012.</p><p>If normal rains prevail, however, production is projected to bounce back strongly, increasing 18.8% in 2012/13, with imports then declining slightly by 2.8%, while consumption of rice resumes its earlier growth path (expanding 5%). Rice demand is growing rapidly across the region, with consumer preferences between imported and domestic rice varying from country to country.</p><p>Rice production in Nigeria, the region’s largest producer (accounting for 39 to 43% of regional rice production) is projected to increase by 3.6% in 2011/12, with imports increasing by 8.7%. However imports are projected to fall back to 2010/11 levels in 2012/13, when Nigerian production is due to increase by a further 5.2%.</p><p><b>West Africa milled rice production: USDA estimates for selected countries (tonnes, MY beginning October)</b></p><table class="renderedtable" border="1" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0">
<tr>
