<p>Sources: USDA <i>GAIN Reports</i> (see below)</p><p>Across the region, ‘governments continue to encourage local rice production to reach self-sufficiency’, in a context where USDA estimates that in MY 2011/12 imports will represent 51% of rice consumption in West Africa (excluding Nigeria, where imports represent 48% of consumption).</p><p>In Senegal, major donor-supported irrigation initiatives are under way in the Senegal River Valley, including provision of subsidised inputs. However, government targets are not being reached, and in some targeted zones the report notes that soil conditions are ill suited to rice production. Efforts are also being made to improve producers’ links with distributors and retailers, in order to strengthen the functioning of domestic rice supply chains.</p><p>In Burkina Faso, stakeholder dialogue structures to define and manage agreements and contracts have largely been in place since 2001. In terms of market trends, there is a shift towards greater rice consumption (from 18.1 kg/person in 2000 to 21 kg/person in 2011, and 50 kg/person in urban areas). While irrigated rice production generates greater yields than rain-fed production (4 to 7 tonnes/hectare compared to 1 t/ha), current government initiatives aim to expand rain-fed production through input and credit support measures. According to USDA, government efforts since 2008 to boost rice production have yielded ‘satisfactory results’, with the area harvested increasing more than threefold.</p><p>In Côte d’Ivoire, efforts to boost production by 200,000 tonnes per annum have now been relaunched, through support to improved rice seed, irrigation and processing. However USDA takes the view that institutional and capacity constraints make this objective unrealistic.</p><p>Mali aspires to increase its rice production (1.1 million tonnes estimated for 2011/12) to 2.7 million tonnes by 2013 and 3.9 million tonnes by 2018, to serve national and regional markets. USDA however sees self-sufficiency as ‘unreachable’, noting that ‘rice imports play an important role in food security’.</p><p>In terms of trade policy, in Senegal rice tariffs vary, ranging from 10 to 32.7%, while in Côte d’Ivoire rice import tariffs are uniformly 5%. In Nigeria, duties range from 5% (brown rice) to 30% (wholly milled rice), with the government planning to increase these to 20% and 50% respectively in order to support local production. Imports are also restricted to sea ports, with imports banned across land borders in order to reduce smuggling. The Nigerian government remains committed to the introduction of a total ban on rice imports by 2015, as an instrument for stimulating local production.&nbsp;</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>USDA, ‘2012 West Africa: Rice annual’, <i>GAIN Report</i>, 6 April 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://gain.fas.usda.gov/Recent%20GAIN%20Publications/Grain%20and%20Feed%20Annual_Dakar_Senegal_4-6-2012.pdf" target="_self">http://gain.fas.usda.gov/Recent%20GAIN%20Publications/Grain%20and%20Feed...</a></p><p>USDA, ‘Nigeria: Grain and feed annual report’, 31 May 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://gain.fas.usda.gov/Recent%20GAIN%20Publications/Grain%20and%20Feed%20Annual_Lagos_Nigeria_5-31-2012.pdf" target="_self">http://gain.fas.usda.gov/Recent%20GAIN%20Publications/Grain%20and%20Feed...</a></p><p><i>Daily Trust</i>, ‘[Federal Government] to establish 100 rice mills nationwide - Minister’, 25 April 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://allafrica.com/stories/201204250586.html" target="_self">http://allafrica.com/stories/201204250586.html</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Whereas the West African region is endowed with significant rice-growing potential, and government policies favour an expansion of production, the region remains dependent on rice imports (mainly from Thailand, but increasingly Vietnam) for almost half of its consumption. These imports of well over 5 million tonnes represent around 20% of rice traded internationally. Nigeria, Benin, Senegal and Côte d’Ivoire are the leading rice importers. Low productivity and high processing and marketing costs hamper the competitiveness of local rice on the regional market. The recent signing by the Nigerian government of a Tripartite Implementation Agreement with a Kenyan investor (Dominion Farms Limited) on the establishment of an integrated rice farm in Taraba State is expected to provide a major boost towards national self- sufficiency, with planned investments projected to increase production by 300,000 tonnes, equivalent to 15% of current Nigerian rice imports.</p><p>Elsewhere in the region, however, with the exception of Burkina Faso, consistent under-attainment of production targets is apparent. West African countries all maintain high tariffs for rice, with Nigeria import levies reaching as high as 150% when additional non-tariff levies are included. Nigeria continues to lead the campaign to classify rice within the 5th ECOWAS CET tariff band (at 50%), in order to maintain regional production capacity. However at the same time it maintains a commitment to banning all rice imports by 2015, raising issues related to consistency within regional and national policy commitments.</p><p>While there is potential for more competitive rice production in West Africa, the question arises over what trade policy framework could most effectively support rice sector development in the region in ways that do not penalise consumers, in a context where around 50% of regional demand is met from imports.</p><p>Lessons could potentially be learnt from the EU’s use of trade policy tools (e.g. the management of TRQs) in the rice sector (see <i>Agritrade</i> Special Report, ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Topics/CAP-reform/Special-report-The-EU-s-agricultural-policy-toolbox-A-sector-by-sector-review" target="_blank">The EU’s agricultural trade policy toolbox</a>’, 13 December 2011, and <i>Agritrade</i> Executive Brief update 2011, ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Rice/Executive-Brief-Update-2011-Rice-sector" target="_blank">Rice sector</a>’).</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
